muscle.description: Any one of the three posterior thigh muscles in between the hip and the knee (from medial to lateral: semimembranosus, semitendinosus and biceps femoris).[3] The hamstrings are quite susceptible to injury.
muscle.action: Flexion of knee, extension of hip

muscle.description: Target for those looking to increase arm muscle appearance. Muscle principally responsible for extension of the elbow joint (straightening of the arm).
muscle.action: Extends forearm, long head extends, adducts arm, Extends shoulder.

muscle.description: The front part of the upper arm. Includes a “short head” and a “long head” that work as a single muscle.
muscle.action: Flexes elbow, flexes and abducts shoulder, supinates radioulnar joint in the forearm.

muscle.description: Originates on the surface of the 1st to 8th ribs at the side of the chest and inserts along the entire anterior length of the medial border of the scapula.
muscle.action: Protracts and stabilizes scapula, assists in upward rotation.

muscle.description: Top half of a muscle group Rectus Abdominis which runs down the front of your core from your ribs to your pubic bone. The Upper part of the "6 pack" abs
muscle.action: Flexion of the lumbar spine

muscle.description: Top half of a muscle group Rectus Abdominis which runs down the front of your core from your ribs to your pubic bone. The Upper part of the "6 pack" abs
muscle.action: Flexion of the lumbar spine

muscle.description: Located on the sides of the abdominals (six-pack muscles) running from the hips to the rib cage. The largest and outermost of the ab muscles of the lateral anterior abdomen.
muscle.action: Flexion of the torso and contralateral rotation of torso.

muscle.description: Muscle of the forearm. It is also capable of both pronation and supination, depending on the position of the forearm.
muscle.action: Flexes the forearm at the elbow

muscle.description: Muscle in the upper arm that flexes the elbow joint. It lies deeper than the biceps brachii, and makes up part of the floor of the region known as the cubital fossa.
muscle.action: Prime mover of elbow flexion.

muscle.description: Acts as the strongest flexor of the hip. The joined psoas and the iliacus muscles. The two muscles are separate in the abdomen, but usually merge in the thigh. The iliopsoas muscle joins to the femur at the lesser trochanter.
muscle.action: Flexion of hip

muscle.description: Relatively small muscle of the upper back that runs from the supraspinous fossa superior portion of the scapula (shoulder blade) to the greater tubercle of the humerus. It is one of the four rotator cuff muscles and also abducts the arm at the shoulder.
muscle.action: Abduction of arm and stabilizes humerus

muscle.description: A large triangular muscle which fills the subscapular fossa and inserts into the lesser tubercle of the humerus and the front of the capsule of the shoulder-joint.
muscle.action: Internally rotates and adducts humerus; stabilizes shoulder

muscle.description: A thick triangular muscle, which occupies the chief part of the infraspinatous fossa. One of the four muscles of the rotator cuff
muscle.action: External rotation of arm and stabilization of glenohumeral joint

muscle.description: A medial rotator and adductor of the humerus and assists the latissimus dorsi in drawing the previously raised humerus downwards and backwards (extension, but not hyper extension). It also helps stabilize the humeral head in the glenoid cavity.
muscle.action: Adduct the humerus, Internal rotation (medial rotation) of the humerus, extend the humerus from flexed position, Depress shoulder

muscle.description: Forearm muscle that acts to flex and (radial) abduct the hand. Visible on the anterior surface of the forearm, just proximal to the wrist, when the wrist is flexed. It it the tendon seen most lateral, closest to the thumb.
muscle.action: Flexion and abduction at wrist.

muscle.description: Lies beside the brachioradialis. A wrist extensor that is innervated by the radial nerve
muscle.action: Extensor at the wrist joint, abducts the hand at the wrist,

muscle.description: Rotate the head to the opposite side or obliquely rotate the head. It also flexes the neck.
muscle.action: Unilaterally: contralateral cervical rotation, ipsilateral cervical flexion Bilaterally: cervical flexion, elevation of sternum and assists in forced inhalation.

muscle.description: Broad, straplike muscle in the back of the neck. It pulls on the base of the skull from the vertebrae in the neck and upper thorax.
muscle.action: Extend, rotate, and laterally flex the head

muscle.description: The lower portion of a group of muscles and tendons which run the length of the spine on the left and the right, from hips to the base of the skull.
muscle.action: Straighten and rotate the back. Extends the vertebral column.

muscle.description: Gives the appearance of a muscular neck.The middle portion of the Trapezius muscle, a large paired surface muscle that extends from the neck to the middle back.
muscle.action: Rotation, retraction, elevation, and depression of shoulder. An upper part which supports the weight of the arm; a middle region, which retracts the scapula; and a lower part which medially rotates and depresses the scapula.

muscle.description: Located on either side of the back and travel from the back of the shoulder all the way down to the hips.
muscle.action: Adducts, extends and internally rotates the arm when the insertion is moved towards the origin. When observing the muscle action of the origin towards the insertion, the lats are a very powerful rotator of the trunk.

muscle.description: Lies in front of the sternal end of the pectoralis major parallel to the margin of the sternum.
muscle.action: There is no apparent physiological function of the sternalis muscle.

muscle.description: The upper portion of the chest muscles.
muscle.action: Clavicular head: flexes the humerus Sternocostal head: horizontal and vertical adduction, extension, and internal rotation of the humerus Depression and abduction of the scapula.

muscle.description: The lower portion of the main chest muscle.
muscle.action: Clavicular head: flexes the humerus Sternocostal head: horizontal and vertical adduction, extension, and internal rotation of the humerus Depression and abduction of the scapula.

muscle.description: The middle portion of the Trapezius muscle, a large paired surface muscle that extends from the neck to the middle back.
muscle.action: Rotation, retraction, elevation, and depression of scapul.

muscle.description: The lower portion of the Trapezius muscle, a large paired surface muscle that extends from the neck to the middle back.
muscle.action: Rotation, retraction, elevation, and depression of scapul.

muscle.description: Thin, triangular muscle, situated at the upper part of the chest, beneath the pectoralis major in the human body.
muscle.action: Stabilizes the scapula by drawing it inferiorly and anteriorly against the thoracic wall, raises ribs in inspiration

muscle.description: Comprise  the rounded corner of the shoulder.
muscle.action: Raise the arm to shoulder level and assist in overhead movements. Shoulder abduction, flexion and extension

muscle.description: A tiny muscle of the thigh, inferior to the iliotibial band. This band, also called the IT band.
muscle.action: Hip - flexion, medial rotation, abduction, knee - lateral rotation, Torso - stabilization

muscle.description: a small muscle located deep in the buttock, behind the gluteus maximus. It runs diagonally from the lower spine to the upper surface of the femur, with the sciatic nerve running underneath or through the muscle.
muscle.action: The piriformis muscle helps the hip rotate, turning the leg and foot outward. External rotator of the thigh

muscle.description: A large triangular muscle, situated on the medial side of the thigh.
muscle.action: Adduction of hip (both portions) flexion of hip (adductor portion) extension of hip (hamstring portion)

muscle.description: The main extensor muscle of the hip. The largest and outermost of the gluteal muscles and makes up a large part of the shape and appearance of each side of the hips. Its thick fleshy mass, in a quadrilateral shape, forms the prominence of the buttocks.
muscle.action: External rotation and extension of the hip joint, supports the extended knee through the iliotibial tract, chief antigravity muscle in sitting and abduction of the hip.

muscle.description: The smallest of the three gluteal muscles, is situated immediately beneath the gluteus medius.
muscle.action: Works in concert with gluteus medius: abduction of the hip; preventing adduction of the hip. Medial rotation of thigh.

muscle.description: a broad, thick, radiating muscle. It is situated on the outer surface of the pelvis.  Its posterior third is covered by the gluteus maximus, its anterior two-thirds by the gluteal aponeurosis, which separates it from the superficial fascia and integument.
muscle.action: Abduction of the hip; preventing adduction of the hip. Medial/internal rotation and flexion of the hip (anterior fibers). Extension and Lateral/external rotation of the hip (posterior fibers)

muscle.description: A large muscle group that includes the four prevailing muscles on the front of the thigh.  It is the great extensor muscle of the knee, forming a large fleshy mass which covers the front and sides of the femur.
muscle.action: Knee extension; Hip flexion (Rectus femoris only)

muscle.description: A powerful muscle in the back part of the lower leg. It runs from just below the knee to the heel.
muscle.action: Involved in standing and walking. Plantar flexion.

muscle.description: Originates in the upper part of outside surface of the tibia and inserts into the medial cuneiform and the foot. This muscle is mostly located near the shin.  It is situated on the lateral side of the tibia; it is thick and fleshy above, tendinous below.
muscle.action: Dorsiflexion and inversion of the foot.

muscle.description: The plantar fascia is a thick, weblike ligament that connects your heel to the front of your foot. Plantar fasciitis (inflammation of this muscle) is one of the most common orthopedic complaints.
muscle.action: The plantar fascia is a thick, weblike ligament that connects your heel to the front of your foot. It acts as a shock absorber and supports the arch of your foot, helping you walk. Plantar fasciitis is one of the most common orthopedic complaints.

muscle.description: The upper portion of a group of muscles and tendons which run the length of the spine on the left and the right, from hips to the base of the skull.
muscle.action: Straighten and rotate the back. Extends the vertebral column.

muscle.description: Upper back muscles that connect between your spine and each of your two shoulder blades. The muscle fibers comprising the rhomboids run on a diagonal.
muscle.action: When they contract, they pull your shoulder blades together. Pulls scapulae medially, rotates scapulae, Holds scapluae into thorax wall

muscle.description: A small triangular muscle, placed between the clavicle and the first rib.
muscle.action: Depression of clavicle. Elevation of first rib

muscle.description: Two small muscular fasciculi, accessories to the tendon of the internal obturator muscle which is received into a groove between them.
muscle.action: Rotate the femur in the hip joint.

muscle.description: A muscle layer of the anterior and lateral (front and side) abdominal wall which is deep to (layered below) the internal oblique muscle. It is a significant component of the core.
muscle.action: Compresses abdominal contents

muscle.description: Passes obliquely across the forearm, and ends in a flat tendon, which is inserted into a rough impression at the middle of the lateral surface of the body of the radius, just distal to the insertion of the supinator.
muscle.action: Pronates the forearm, turning the hand posteriorly. If the elbow is flexed to a right angle, then pronator teres will turn the hand so that the palm faces inferiorly. It is assisted in this action by pronator quadratus.

muscle.description: A narrow, intrinsic shoulder muscle that extends from the lateral border of the scapula to the greater tubercle (or tuberosity) of the humerus.
muscle.action: The primary function is to modulate the action of the deltoid, preventing the humeral head from sliding upward as the arm is abducted. It also laterally rotates the arm, stabilizes humerus

muscle.description: A broad muscle in the posterior compartment of the forearm, curved around the upper third of the radius.
muscle.action: Supinates forearm. Encircling the radius, supinator brings the hand into the supinated position. In contrast to the biceps brachii, it is able to do this in all positions of elbow flexion and extension.

muscle.description: Lies deep inside your leg. It runs down the lower leg all the way to the big toe.
muscle.action: Helps you flex your big toe so that you can walk and hold yourself upright while on your tiptoes.
